{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608734"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:35:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16012"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16012"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.06,0.29,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"6866"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20822"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe secondary palate develops between weeks 8-12 of gestation. During this period, bilateral palatal shelves undergo a complex series of movements and fusion events.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the palatal shelves during embryonic development?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Separate the oral and nasal cavities","Form the floor of the orbit","Create the anterior hard palate","Generate the nasal septum","Develop the tongue musculature"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the \u003Cstrong\u003Epalatal shelves separate the oral and nasal cavities\u003C/strong\u003E through a complex process of growth, elevation and fusion. Initially, the palatal shelves grow vertically alongside the developing tongue, then rapidly elevate to a horizontal position above the tongue around week 8. The shelves then grow towards each other and fuse in the midline by week 12.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreate the anterior hard palate\u003C/strong\u003E - The primary palate anterior to the incisive foramen forms from fusion of the medial nasal processes, not the palatal shelves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate the nasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E - The nasal septum develops from the frontonasal prominence and grows downward to meet the palatal shelves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForm the floor of the orbit\u003C/strong\u003E - The orbital floor develops from the maxillary process and is not related to palatal shelf development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDevelop the tongue musculature\u003C/strong\u003E - Tongue muscles develop from occipital somites that migrate into the floor of the primitive oral cavity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFailure of palatal shelf elevation or fusion results in cleft palate, one of the most common congenital anomalies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Palatal shelves elevate and fuse during weeks 8-12 of development to separate the oral and nasal cavities.","Failure of palatal shelf elevation or fusion results in cleft palate.","The secondary palate forms posterior to the incisive foramen from paired palatal shelves."],"references":["Ansari A, Bordoni B. Embryology, Face. [Updated 2024 Jan 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545202/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16012"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T21:39:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T21:42:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73471"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"ht